english:
  title: An Explanation of the Character Heart
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The heart is the union of Principle and Vital Force. What precedes Heaven and Earth without beginning, what follows Heaven and Earth without ending—this is Principle and Vital Force. This we call the Great Ultimate. The Great Ultimate is Principle; its movement and stillness are Vital Force. Thus is the heart of Heaven, Earth, and all things constituted. The Limitless that is also the Great Ultimate—this is the heart of Heaven and Earth. All things each possessing one Great Ultimate—this is the heart of all things.

    Among all things, humanity alone obtained Vital Force that is upright and unobstructed. Therefore, the Principle residing in this Vital Force lacks nothing of completeness. All other things obtained Vital Force that is partial and blocked. Therefore, the Principle residing in their Vital Force cannot be fully realized. Here lies the distinction between humans and things. Yet even the upright and unobstructed is not without its inequalities of clarity and turbidity, purity and mixture. Thus arise differences of wisdom and foolishness, worthiness and unworthiness. And even the partial and blocked possesses some glimmer of original knowing. Thus there emerge relationships approaching those of father and son, ruler and subject—bonds of gratitude and distinction. Here we see that the heart of both humans and things is nothing but the union of Principle and Vital Force.

    Speak only of Vital Force, and the heart becomes merely one organ among the five viscera. Speak only of Principle, and the heart becomes merely the collective name of the five natures. Only when Principle and Vital Force are united do we truly call it the heart. Should Principle and Vital Force separate, then Principle remains Principle and Vital Force remains Vital Force—we cannot call this the heart.

    Shun commanded Yu, saying: "The human heart is precarious; the heart of the Way is subtle." In these words, he divided the Principle and Vital Force mingling in the span of a hand's breadth, establishing the warning to refine the singular and grasp the center. This is the wellspring of the science of the heart for ten thousand generations. Thousands of years later came Zhou Dunyi's Explanation of the Diagram of the Great Ultimate, which Cheng Yi and Zhu Xi elaborated and expounded. The doctrine of Principle and Vital Force became luminous and complete. How fortunate are the scholars of this age! To understand this is to understand the principle of life and death, to make living harmonious and death peaceful.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'five viscera' (五臟) and 'five natures' (五性) refer to the five organs and their corresponding virtues in classical Chinese philosophy and medicine.
  - key: ''
    value: Shun's instruction to Yu is from the ancient text transmitted as the Great Plan (洪範). The 'human heart' and 'heart of the Way' represent the distinction between desire-driven impulses and moral principle.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhou Dunyi (周敦頤), Cheng Yi (程頤), and Zhu Xi (朱熹) were foundational neo-Confucian philosophers whose syntheses of Principle and Vital Force theory shaped East Asian intellectual history.
